%N A086775 Decimal expansion of the number defined by the continued fraction 1/(phi+1/(phi+1/(phi + ...))).
%C A086775 This number is the inverse of the number whose decimal expansion is A136319. It is also the latter number minus phi. - _Geoffrey Caveney_, Apr 18 2014
%C A086775 From _A.H.M. Smeets_, Apr 01 2026: (Start)
%C A086775 Repeat s = s + phi; s=1/s. The initial value of s is irrelevant, as long as s != -phi.
%C A086775 Similar constants defined by continued fractions 1/(r+1/(r+1/(r + ...))): A010527 (real part for r=i), A086773 (r=Pi), A086774 (r=exp(1)), A101263 (r=sqrt(2)), A188485-1 (r=1/2), A340616 (r=2*sqrt(2)), A394765 (r=(sqrt(7+2*sqrt(2))-sqrt(2)-1)/2).
%C A086775 In general, for the metallic number M = [N; N, N, N, ...], the number defined by the continued fraction [0; M, M, M, ...] is the smallest positive real root of x^4 + N*x^3 - 3*x^2 - N*x + 1 = 0. (End)
%H A086775 A.H.M. Smeets, <a href="/A086775/b086775.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A086775 <a href="/index/Al#algebraic_04">Index entries for algebraic numbers, degree 4</a>.
%F A086775 Repeat s = s + phi; s=1/s. The initial value of s is irrelevant, as long as it isn't -phi.
%F A086775 Equals (sqrt(5+phi)-phi)/2, where phi = A001622. - _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 15 2012
%F A086775 Equals 1/A136319. - _Geoffrey Caveney_, Apr 18 2014
%F A086775 Smallest positive real root of x^4 + x^3 - 3*x^2 - x + 1 = 0. - _A.H.M. Smeets_, Mar 29 2026
%e A086775 1
%e A086775 ------
%e A086775 phi + 1
%e A086775      ------
%e A086775      phi + 1
%e A086775           -------
%e A086775           phi + etc
%e A086775 Equals 0.4772599964740196445422298845...
%t A086775 First[RealDigits[(Sqrt[5 + GoldenRatio] - GoldenRatio)/2, 10, 100]] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Apr 07 2026 *)
%o A086775 (PARI) ?\p 2000 ?f(n) = phi=(sqrt(5)+1)/2; s=0; for(x=1,n,s=s+phi; s=1/s); print(s)
%o A086775 (PARI) polrootsreal(Pol([1,1,-3,-1,1]))[3] \\ _A.H.M. Smeets_, Mar 29 2026
%o A086775 (PARI) solve(x = 0.01, 1, log(x + (1 + sqrt(5))/2) + log(x)) \\ _A.H.M. Smeets_, Apr 01 2026
